<font color="#FF0000">A FEW QUESTIONS ON VIETNAM</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 18  1:27:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Morris,<br>
     Have gone into high schools (when they can find the time) in Philadelphia to teach a period covering the war.  Even 22 years after Saigon's fall and 29 after Tet, the subject is still too sensitive politically for text book manufacturers.  There probably will not be anything formal until Texas decides something is OK; as they centralize purchases.                                                                                                                   What to ask?  What is the country of Vietnam and its people like?  What were the war's roots in history, culture, geography and politics?  Why were we there?  How informed and accurate were the opinions, policies and decisions that got us there?  How was the war conducted?  What was it like for the troops who served? - expect innumerable answers to this, as the war was different for everyone depending on time period, place and assignment.                                                                                           What not to ask?  Many vets really get tired of hearing, &quot;How many people did you kill?&quot; especially as the first question.  I know several guys who refuse to answer that question either way, and say so right off.                                                                              The toughest question I've got so far was at a high school for kids that are disciplinary problems.  It was: &quot;If you know what you know now; would you still go.&quot;  Since I was an officer when I got orders; I would have gone, but probably would have said a few things that would get me in trouble.                                                                                                                You might want to check out the lengthy bios for the participants listed for the FORUM section.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


